result.execSummary:
The defendant Dawn R Kuehni was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Business Setting >$2500-$5000 [Modifiers: Penalty - Theft >$2500-$5000], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(b).
  • Theft-Business Setting <=$2500 [Modifiers: Penalty-Theft if Value <=$2500], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Pay restitution in the amount of $64,889.68 and restitution surcharge. Restitution is to be paid in full by equal monthly installments for thirty-two (32) months commencing on January 1, 2016.
---------------------------

Pay court costs.   If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment may be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and governmental entities for the balance due.  Collections may include income assignment.
---------------------------

IT IS HEREBY ORDERED THAT the defendant's excess work release funds be applied to any & all outstanding Court obligations while serving his mandatory jail sentence.
---------------------------

Provide biological specimen to state crime lab for DNA analysis, and pay DNA analysis surcharge.  The defendant must pay Department of Corrections Supervision fees. Enter into and successfully complete any treatment or counseling as determined by her Agent. Must notify every potential employer about her conviction and the nature of the crime.

8:32 am  Court in session.  Case called.  Appearances given.  
ADA Diane M. Donohoo appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Defendant Dawn R Kuehni appeared.  
Probation Agent Scott Pederson appeared.  
Court makes record that the Court knows the victim on a business level.  
Court asks if Ms. Kuehni has any objection to this Court proceeding.  Ms. Kuehni has no objection.  
Agent Pederson indicates it is Dept.'s position that Ms. Kuehni has made a good faith to pay.  
Agent Pederson also realizes there was specific language in the JOC with regard to specific payments that were to be made.  
Response by Atty Donohoo to Court's questions.  She does not believe defendant has made a good faith effort.  
Statement by victim, Mr. Ghiselli.  He provides pictures to the Court.  
8:40 am  Statement by victim that in-laws paid for new driveway.  She did purchase a new car.  Pmts are roughly $300.  There is also a Dodge Ram and there are payments on that vehicle.  She states she is really trying to take care of this.  Response by Ms. Kuehni to Court's question as to what happened to the money that she took.  Amount of restitution owed is still $50,961.12.  Probation is due to expire on September 3rd.  Atty Donohoo is asking for probation to be extended for a minimum of 2 years.  She believes there should be jail time imposed based upon the 2 new vehicles that have been purchase.  8:44 am  Response by Ms. Kuehni.  Response by Agent as to current balance of amount owed.  8:46 am  Court finds Ms. Kuehni has not made a good faith effort.  Court orders 3 year extension of probation and Orders 6 months Jail, imposed and stayed upon payment of $1500 per month.  If she does not make payments, Court wants this brought back to Court for a further probation review hearing.  Response by Court to question as to whether this can be modified by Agent.  Court advises it would need to be brought back before the Court.  Agent to submit Order to Court.  8:48 am  Court in recess.

records.addlTxt:
2:33 pm  Court in session.  Case called.  Appearances given.  
Diane M. Donohoo appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Defendant Dawn R Kuehni in court with attorney Timothy Mistrioty.  
Also present is Probation Agent Amanda Swenson.  
Matter is before the Court based upon a letter the Court received from Probation Amanda Swenson.  The Agent's concern is with regard to the required monthly payment toward restitution and Ms. Kuehni's inability to pay that amount at this time.  Court did received a letter from Mr. Ghiselli.  Attorney Donohoo states there is no Motion to Modify the sentence that has been filed.  Court agrees that it does not have the authority to do anything at his point.  Statement by Probation Agent Swenson.  The Department does not  feel it is egregious enough to warrant revocation or a jail sanction.  The Dept. reviews all of the defendant's financials and trie to come up with the most realistic way to pay.  The Department does not have that flexability in this case because of the required payments set forth in the Judgment of Conviction.  Ms. Swenson completely understands that the victim wants to be paid and made whole.  Probation Agent Swenson indicates that she has reviewed the letter of victim and indicates there are things in the letter that are not true.  Agent Swenson proposes possibly scheduling a further review hearing in 3 months.  Discussion between Court and Agent as to reason for any probation review heaiing.  DOC is looking for more time and they are doing everything in their power to try to collect the restitution.  Response by Attorney Donohoo.  Response by Attorney Mistrioty that Ms. Kuehni is committed to getting restitution paid within the probation period.  They need 3 to 6 months to get this going.  She was released from Jail in December.  In January she got full time employment.  She brings home just over $--- every two weeks.  When her electronic monitoring ends, there will be more money to apply toward restitution.  She will also be able to work more hours and can look for a 2nd job.  Court believes it it wholly under direction of DOC to determine as to how to proceed.  The Court is encouraged by what Attorney Mistirioty has to say.  Court is not going to take any action at this time but if there is a request by the Dept for sanctions, the court will give it serious consideration.
